{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Place a bowl onto mixing bowl lid and weigh liver and milk into it (add enough milk to ensure liver is completely covered). Set aside for 1 hour. Remove liver from milk and pat dry with paper towel. Remove and discard any skin and fat. Cut liver into thin slivers on an angle, from the front (thin part) to the back (thick part) and set aside.","Place onion into mixing bowl and chop <b>3 sec\/speed 5<b>. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula.","Add bacon and butter and cook <b>5 min\/Varoma\/\/speed 1<b>.","Add tomato sauce, Worcestershire sauce, salt and  pepper and cook <b>2 min\/100°C\/\/speed 1<b><strong>, without measuring cup.<\/strong> ","Place a bowl onto mixing bowl lid and weigh flour into it. Toss liver pieces in flour and shake off any excess flour. Add liver to mixing bowl and cook <b>230-3 min\/100°C\/\/speed 1<b>, until just cooked (see Tips). Garnish with parsley and serve with mashed potatoes and peas (see Tips)."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["500 g lamb's liver (lamb's fry - see Tips)","300 - 500 g milk","200 g brown onion, cut into halves","6 rindless bacon rashers (approx. 230 g), cut into 3-4 cm pieces","50 g salted butter","60 g tomato sauce","40 g Worcestershire sauce","¼ tsp salt","¼ tsp ground black pepper","100 - 150 g plain flour, for dusting","2 - 3 sprigs fresh flat-leaf parsley, roughly chopped","mashed potatoes and cooked peas, to serve (see Tips)"]}],"id":"r238987","imageLink":"https:\/\/3.bp.blogspot.com\/-nhT16l-vzcs\/XZQHsDGDGcI\/AAAAAAAAcLE\/SqNegqs095cCrzHyazZ0u6f547KMr4vwwCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_pCYtaD8D69UbO3Ms.png","title":"Lamb's fry with bacon","publishedAt":"2018-07-30T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"41.2 g","fat":"31.4 g","uom":"per 1 portion","carbohydrates":"56.4 g","calories":"2874.6 kJ \/ 684.4 kcal"},"usefulItems":"bowl, paper towel","hintsAndTricks":["We recommend purchasing lamb's liver (lamb's fry) from your butcher to get the best quality.","Soaking liver in milk reduces any toughness.","Lamb's fry should be pink in the centre when cooked. Do not be tempted to continue cooking or it will become tough.","To make mashed potatoes, please refer to <i>The Basic Cookbook<\/i> or the <i>Everyday Cookbook<\/i> for the recipe. You can cook mash and peas while the livers are soaking, then keep warm in a thermal serving bowl.","For a lighter meal, simply serve lamb's fry on buttered toast."],"basicInfo":["easy","15m","1h 20m","6 portions"]}